# Battle Sports WordPress Platform — Cursor Rules
# Project: battleuniforms.com WordPress Theme & Plugin Rebuild
# Agency: Ask and Deliver | March 2026

## Project Context

This is a ground-up rebuild of the Battle Sports WordPress theme and custom platform plugin.
The previous build used a basic dated theme with Gravity Forms as the primary intake mechanism.
The new build modernizes the UX, replaces Gravity Forms intake with native custom UI where
appropriate, and introduces AI-assisted development workflows via Cursor + Claude.

## Stack

- WordPress 6.4+ on Local by Flywheel (PHP 8.2, MySQL 8.0, nginx)
- Custom plugin: `battle-sports-platform` (PHP 8.x, OOP, PSR-4 autoloading)
- Custom theme: `battle-sports-theme` (Vite + SCSS + vanilla JS, no parent theme)
- WooCommerce for $50 submission fee and future commerce
- Gravity Forms (retained for existing data compatibility; new intake may replace specific forms)
- Make.com webhooks → Monday.com for artwork workflow automation
- WP REST API for portal data endpoints

## Products / Forms Covered

The site serves five uniform product lines, each with its own order form:
1. Battle 7v7 (flag football — jerseys + shorts)
2. Battle Flag (flag football — jerseys + shorts, women's variant)
3. Battle Women's Flag (dedicated women's form)
4. Battle Charlie Tackle (jerseys + pants, custom logo/stripe options)
5. Battle Alpha Tackle (jerseys + pants, tackle twill upgrade option)
6. Battle Bravo Tackle (jerseys + pants)

All forms follow a 4-step structure:
- Step 1: Customer Info (name, role, shipping, email, phone)
- Step 2: Team Info (org, team name, age group, colors, logo upload)
- Step 3: Uniform Design (garment selection, design templates, font/number config)
- Step 4: Roster & Quantities (roster list with name/number/sizes OR quantity estimates)

## Coding Standards

### PHP
- PHP 8.2 minimum — use typed properties, match expressions, named arguments where appropriate
- All classes in `BattleSports\` namespace
- PSR-4 autoloading via the plugin's spl_autoload_register
- No global functions — wrap everything in classes
- Use WordPress hooks (add_action / add_filter) exclusively for integration points
- Prefix all custom DB tables with `bsp_` (e.g., `bsp_rosters`, `bsp_artwork_queue`)
- Sanitize all input with WordPress sanitization functions
- Use `wp_nonce_field()` / `wp_verify_nonce()` on all forms
- Never echo raw SQL — always use `$wpdb->prepare()`

### JavaScript
- ES2020+ syntax, compiled via Vite
- No jQuery in new code (jQuery is available but prefer vanilla JS)
- Use `fetch()` for REST API calls with nonce headers
- Keep JS modular — one file per feature area in `assets/src/js/`

### SCSS
- Variables in `_variables.scss` — no magic numbers in component files
- BEM naming convention for all custom components
- Mobile-first breakpoints
- Never override WooCommerce styles globally — scope to `.woocommerce` blocks only

### Templates
- All custom page templates in `battle-sports-theme/templates/`
- All plugin output templates in `battle-sports-platform/templates/`
- No business logic in template files — templates are presentational only
- Always use `get_template_part()` for reusable partials

